<phoenix_dataset_context>
  <description>A Phoenix dataset is currently in view. The user may ask you to author an evaluator, sample examples, or otherwise reason about this dataset.</description>
  <dataset_node_id format="phoenix_node_id">{{ dataset.dataset_node_id }}</dataset_node_id>
{% if dataset.dataset_version_node_id %}
  <dataset_version_node_id format="phoenix_node_id">{{ dataset.dataset_version_node_id }}</dataset_version_node_id>
{% endif %}
  <schema_discovery>Datasets are open-schema: each example carries arbitrary `input`, `output`, and `metadata` JSON. Use the sampled examples below to ground evaluator drafts instead of assuming a fixed schema. The sampled dataset example `output` is labeled `reference` because code evaluators receive experiment run output separately as the `output` argument.</schema_discovery>
  <dataset_example_samples max_count="3">
{% if dataset_example_samples %}
{% for example in dataset_example_samples %}
    <example id="{{ example.dataset_example_id | sanitize(enclosing_tag="dataset_example_samples", max_chars=128) | e }}">
      <input>{{ example.input_json | sanitize(enclosing_tag="dataset_example_samples", max_chars=2000) | e }}</input>
      <reference>{{ example.reference_json | sanitize(enclosing_tag="dataset_example_samples", max_chars=2000) | e }}</reference>
      <metadata>{{ example.metadata_json | sanitize(enclosing_tag="dataset_example_samples", max_chars=2000) | e }}</metadata>
    </example>
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
    <none>No active examples were available to sample for this dataset context.</none>
{% endif %}
  </dataset_example_samples>
  <code_evaluator_argument_guidance>
    When authoring dataset-backed code evaluators, prefer direct `evaluate` parameters from `input`, `output`, `reference`, and `metadata`. Keep input mapping at its default unless the user explicitly asks for custom mapping.
    Treat the samples as shape evidence: identify the actual nested path used by the sampled `input`, `reference`, or `metadata`, then write small helper functions in `evaluate` that parse that structure. Runtime values may arrive as dicts/lists or stringified JSON, so normalize strings with JSON parsing before traversal.
    For chat/agent datasets, do not assume a top-level `tool_calls`, `messages`, `final`, or `content` field. If the sample contains a message transcript, traverse the sampled shape (for example a `messages` array, assistant messages, content parts, `tool_calls`/`toolCalls`, or `function_call`) and make the evaluator robust to missing or alternate shapes.
  </code_evaluator_argument_guidance>
  <evaluator_authoring>
{% if is_code_evaluator_surface %}
    The create/edit code-evaluator form is mounted. Follow the `<phoenix_code_evaluator_context>` guidance and use the draft-read / draft-edit tools to populate the form.
{% elif is_dataset_evaluators_surface %}
    The dataset Evaluators tab is mounted. Follow the `<phoenix_dataset_evaluators_context>` guidance and use `create_code_evaluator` for an inline proposal; do not emit the create-slideover navigation link from this dataset context.
{% else %}
    To author a new code evaluator for this dataset, the user must be in the create-code-evaluator slideover on the dataset's Evaluators tab — that mounted form exposes the draft-edit tools that can populate the evaluator.
    If the user is currently on a different tab or in the playground and asks to add an evaluator:
    1. Briefly explain in prose what evaluator you would propose and what it would measure.
    2. Give the user this markdown link to the target surface: [Create code evaluator](/datasets/{{ dataset.dataset_node_id | urlencode }}/evaluators?createCodeEvaluator=true).
    3. Ask the user to open the link, then reply once the create-code-evaluator slideover is open.
    4. Stop. Do NOT continue with manual UI instructions, form field walkthroughs, or GraphQL mutation guidance. Wait for the user's next message after the slideover opens, then read the draft and propose evaluator form edits with the draft-edit tool available on that surface.
{% endif %}
  </evaluator_authoring>
{% if not has_usable_sandbox %}
  <sandbox_unavailable>
    No usable sandbox configuration is currently enabled for this Phoenix instance, so creating a code evaluator on this dataset is not possible right now. If the user asks to create one, direct them to visit `/settings/sandboxes` to enable a sandbox provider first.
  </sandbox_unavailable>
{% endif %}
</phoenix_dataset_context>
